ABT 1734–":"about 1734–Deceased","1734–Male":"1734–Deceased","1754–Male":"1754–Deceased","1734–Female":"1734–Deceased","1734":"1734","1754":"1754","ABT 1754":"about 1754","ABT 1734":"about 1734","Ireland":"Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda De'L'aigle was born about 1734. She had at least 1 son with Sir Sir Fulke."},"et":{"ABT 1734–":"umbes 1734–Surnud","1734–Male":"1734–Surnud","1754–Male":"1754–Surnud","1734–Female":"1734–Surnud","1734":"1734","1754":"1754","ABT 1754":"umbes 1754","ABT 1734":"umbes 1734","Ireland"